replies.body:
So here is my argument on the matter, and this is based on what I have seen through spectating and playing.

Back when there was the Spirit of the Spectral Wraith, these were the junglers who considered building the item at all: {{champion:32}} {{champion:131}} {{champion:60}} {{champion:28}} {{champion:9}} {{champion:105}} {{champion:76}} {{champion:20}} {{champion:78}} {{champion:113}} {{champion:154}} 

So from this list, we can take {{champion:154}}{{champion:32}}  {{champion:20}} {{champion:113}} out because they were played as tanks anyway (though {{champion:32}} used it quite often). Then we can remove {{champion:76}} {{champion:78}} {{champion:105}} {{champion:131}} because they were mostly played in solo lanes anyway ({{champion:131}} would jungle occasionally, but she was mostly in a solo lane). {{champion:60}} always built the tank item and {{champion:28}} built the AD or tank item. That leaves {{champion:9}} being the ONLY competitively played AP jungler. {{champion:60}} {{champion:28}} {{champion:76}} and {{champion:131}} all received nerfs and/or reworks in their kits over time, and they were not played much anymore ({{champion:76}} was awful because it took a while to finalize where they wanted her to be in terms of power). But in the jungle, the only junglers who were building the AP item were {{champion:9}} {{champion:76}} and the occasional {{champion:131}}. Now that Runeglaive took the place of Magus, we see {{champion:60}} {{champion:28}} {{champion:131}} {{champion:76}} {{champion:105}}{{champion:245}}  all being played in the jungle with the AP item, even though {{champion:245}} and {{champion:105}} build the tank item more often than the AP one. Jungle diversity actually rose with the addition of the Runeglaive. Yes it hurt {{champion:9}} a lot, but balance changes directly to him can bring him up to par with laners and possibly supports, because right now he doesn't have much identity anymore. But diversity in the jungle is higher with Runeglaive, because before it came along there weren't many AP junglers that were being played outside of normal games (there were really only 1.5 {{champion:9}} and sometimes {{champion:76}} ), and they were mostly cheese anyway. No one played them in ranked games unless they were 100% committed to the style, but they were a minority. And Cinderhulk has given the Tanks {{champion:32}} {{champion:20}} {{champion:113}} {{champion:154}} a place in the jungle and they no longer need the AP.

Just for a perspective visual, here is a before and after.

Before

AD: {{champion:266}} {{champion:28}} {{champion:59}} {{champion:121}} {{champion:64}} {{champion:11}} {{champion:56}} {{champion:2}} {{champion:80}} {{champion:107}} {{champion:35}} {{champion:48}} {{champion:23}} {{champion:5}}  {{champion:254}} {{champion:62}} 

AP: {{champion:9}} {{champion:76}} 

Tank: {{champion:32}} {{champion:31}} {{champion:36}} {{champion:60}} {{champion:120}} {{champion:57}} {{champion:75}} {{champion:111}} {{champion:33}} {{champion:113}} {{champion:20}}  {{champion:102}} {{champion:72}} {{champion:77}} {{champion:106}} {{champion:19}} {{champion:154}} 

After

AD: {{champion:266}} {{champion:59}} {{champion:24}} {{champion:121}} {{champion:64}} {{champion:11}} {{champion:56}} {{champion:80}} {{champion:107}} {{champion:35}} {{champion:48}} {{champion:23}} {{champion:77}} {{champion:5}}  {{champion:254}} {{champion:62}} 

AP: {{champion:131}} {{champion:245}} {{champion:60}} {{champion:28}} {{champion:76}} {{champion:78}} 

Tank: {{champion:32}} {{champion:31}} {{champion:245}} {{champion:79}} {{champion:120}} {{champion:75}} {{champion:20}} {{champion:2}} {{champion:33}} {{champion:421}} {{champion:113}} {{champion:98}} {{champion:102}} {{champion:14}} {{champion:72}} {{champion:106}} {{champion:19}} {{champion:154}}

In the grand scheme of things, with all the changes going around, jungle diversity is at an all time high, with the most dramatic change in the AP slot.
